x4freetext: 228 mg/cm2 Be target.
The experimental apparatus
includes NSCL NaI(Tl) array, large acceptance S800
superconducting spectrograph. The NSCL NaI(Tl) array
consists of 38 detectors, which are arranged in 3
concentric rings, of 11 (inner), 17 (middle) and 10
(outer) detectors, respectively. The radii of the
three detector rings are 10.8 cm, 16.9 cm and 21.8 cm,
respectively. The crystals are cylindrical,
approximately 18.0 cm long and 5.75 cm in diameter
and placed into a 0.45 mm thick aluminum shield. A 1
cm thick quartz window is attached to each end.
Optical glue was used to connect 5 cm in diameter
photomultiplier tubes (PMTs) to each window. To
shield the NaI(Tl) detector array from photons
originating at the phoswich detector, and natural
radioactivity, the entire array was placed into a 16
cm thick lead shield.
Radioactive beams of carbon at
approximately 60 MeV/nucleon were produced by
fragmentation of an 80 MeV/nucleon 22Ne primary beam
on a thick 9Be target. These secondary beams were
purified in the A1200 fragment separator by the
combination of magnetic analysis and an intermediate
degrader. The resulting beam was delivered to the
experimental setup, consisting of three parts: a
dispersion-matching beam line, a target surrounded by
an array of NaI(Tl) gamma detectors, and the S800
spectrograph used for detecting the projectile
residues from the reaction. The excited states of the
residues were tagged by an inner ring of 11
cylindrical NaI(Tl) scintillators surrounding the
target. Each scintillator was read out by two
photomultiplier tubes, one at each end, thus allowing
the determination of both the energy and the
interaction point of the photon in the detector. The
position information provided by the array made it
possible to correct for the Doppler shift in the
energy of the gamma rays emitted by the fast
(beta=0.34) residues.
The intensities of the excited states of the
residues were extracted by fitting the measured
gamma-ray spectra with the line shapes generated by
simulations withe the Monte Carlo code GEANT. The
reliability of the simulations was tested by
comparing measured and simulated gamma-ray spectra
from calibration sources. The longitudinal momentum
distributions of the residues were reconstructed with
the ion optics code COSY INFINITY.
